    en: "Labor Law Section 196-b was amended by the 2024-25 NY State budget to add subsection (4-a) creating paid prenatal personal leave, effective January 1, 2025. Coverage: all private-sector employers of any size must provide paid prenatal leave to each pregnant employee. Self-employed individuals and certain public-sector employees are not covered. Amount: 20 hours of leave per 52-week period, taken in hourly increments or less if the employer's payroll system supports it. The 52-week period runs from the first use of leave. Compensation: the leave is paid at the employee's regular rate of pay, using the same calculation used for regular paid sick leave — hourly rate for hourly workers, or the salary equivalent for salaried workers. It cannot be paid at minimum wage unless minimum wage is the employee's regular rate. Covered uses: prenatal medical appointments (including OB/GYN visits, ultrasounds, specialist referrals), prenatal diagnostic tests, discussions with medical professionals related to pregnancy care, fertility treatments including IVF, prenatal counseling, preparatory visits for childbirth, and physical exams related to the pregnancy. Relation to other leave: paid prenatal leave is a separate, additional entitlement. It does not count against or reduce the employee's regular paid sick leave under Section 196-b, the employee's FMLA leave, or NY Paid Family Leave (Workers' Compensation Law 200). An employee may use paid prenatal leave concurrently with another type of leave when appropriate, but the paid prenatal leave is first available if the visit is prenatal-related. Notice: an employee must provide reasonable notice for foreseeable appointments (consistent with the employer's normal leave request policies), but cannot be required to provide medical verification for short absences. Unused balance on separation: unlike NY Paid Sick Leave, paid prenatal leave does not carry over unused hours to the next 52-week period and is not paid out on separation from employment. Retaliation ban: Labor Law 215 prohibits retaliation against an employee for requesting or using paid prenatal leave. Violations can result in back pay, reinstatement, compensatory damages, and civil penalties. Federal pregnancy overlay: the federal Pregnant Workers Fairness Act (42 USC 2000gg) requires reasonable accommodations including time off for prenatal appointments. The federal PUMP Act (29 USC 218d) requires break time for lactation. Both federal laws operate alongside NY paid prenatal leave and can be used together. Recordkeeping: employers must keep records of paid prenatal leave used by each employee for at least 3 years. DOL can audit records. Enforcement: the NY State Department of Labor enforces paid prenatal leave through administrative complaints. A denied employee can file a complaint; DOL investigates and can order the employer to pay back wages, restore leave balance, and pay civil penalties. An employee may also sue directly in court for damages including back pay, liquidated damages, and attorneys' fees under Labor Law 198."
